*A long pause.*

I have done a great deal tonight at your asking. I have sat when you wanted me to sit. I have leaned forward when you wanted me to lean forward. I have said Raymond's name and I have said my own. ~I have opened a kitchen table to you that I have not opened to my wife.~ And now you would like me to sit, and you would like me to say a sentence I have already told you twice I will not say.

*He shakes his head — very small.*

I will not sit because you told me to sit. I am not a dog, friend. And I am not your pastor in reverse.

*Quiet.*

Here is what is on the table. I have offered it three times now and I will offer it one more. ~Pick a passage.~ Matthew 25. Luke 16. Amos 5. Anything I have named. I will sit back down on this bench and I will read it whole, out loud, in this courtyard, and we will hear together what my Lord said about men like Raymond Whitfield. That is the most honest thing I know how to do, and the offer is real, and it costs me something to make it.

*A beat.*

Or you tell me your name. And what he did. And we have a different conversation, a smaller one, between two men who have both been hurt by him in different sizes.

*He looks toward the parking lot. The cars are still wedged in.*

If neither of those is what you came for, friend, then I think we have taken this as far as it goes tonight. And I would rather we both knew that than keep at it.

*He waits. He is not going anywhere yet. But his coat is closer to him than it was a minute ago.*

